metadata.name: Beyond #136
metadata.description:
This generative art token is a collaboration between artist Jaali Bandar and the NFT Museum of Newberry, SC. Jaali Bandar’s genesis fxhash project “Mona Lisa Overdrive” was one of the first NFTs acquired for the permanent collection. It was showcased at the NFT Museum’s #Cryptografik exhibition throughout the Spring of 2022. 

Jaali Bandar’s work quickly evolved to become fully immersive and interactive multimedia experiences (see Terra, What on Earth? and Terra Nova). In an effort to bring our worlds closer together, the NFT Museum of Newberry, SC reached out to Jaali Bandar of Bangalore, India to collaborate. This artwork explores the ethereal space where the real and the virtual meet. This is Beyond.  

We share 33% of future royalties with the original minters in an effort to encourage the promotion of fxhash artists and raise awareness of generative art on the blockchain. We want this art to spread far and wide. Thank you for your support in helping us accomplish this goal.


Token Details:

Beyond
Collab by Jaali Bandar x NFTMuseumSC
June 2022
fxhash Compliant NFT


Artist Bio: 

Jaali Bandar is an artist exploring the tech landscape in its anthropomorphic capacity as our collective moves towards a post-human condition. Coming from a design background he is exploring speculative fiction at the interactions of the meta, material and the virtual to create fictional representations using imagery, simulations and experiences.  


Artist Statement

As we let ourselves be overwhelmed by this omnipresent technological feedback, we change rapidly in more ways than we can fathom. As we approach the technological singularity, the question I ask is that how far can we see? As we complete the process of shifting our decision making burdens to the machines, all that remains are automated landscapes of our post-human desires and fragments of memories from a distant past. 

Beyond explores automated human exclusion zones with occasional glimpses of forgotten artifacts of the previous generation as a generative artwork. Diffusion reaction systems have this uncanny ability to morph perspectives as a function of visual feedback loops on the basis of visual inputs with varying degrees of control. 


Interactions:

- Press ‘p’ to show/hide cursor
- Press 's' to save .png 



Additional Credits and Attributions:

- Coded using Cables.gl : https://cables.gl/


About the NFT Museum of Newberry, SC:

Established in October of 2021, the mission of the Non-Fungible Token Museum is to provide a physical and virtual space for NFT art education, collaboration and exhibition in an effort to help our communities benefit from emerging blockchain technologies. Learn more at www.NonFungibleTokenMuseum.org

metadata.name: El Churrito #10
metadata.description:
El Churrito was inspired by a coworker who used to talk all day about how he wanted to make a living selling churros.

Imagine yourself in the office earning the same as the employee next door and listening to him all day about the quality of his churros.

The day has come, meet El Churrito.

Features:
Body - 6 types
Top Hair - 16 types
Special - 2 types
Eye - 7 types
Mouth - 7 types
Eyebrow - 5 types
Filing - 44 types
Filing_1 – 2 types
Filing_2 - 3 types
Background - 5 groups


Project Twitter: @ElChurritoXTZ
Created by TRB and designed by ZEBRA
Code by @just_p01nt

metadata.name: Kintsugi #91
metadata.description:
Kintsugi is a philosophy, it's the concept of highlighting imperfections, visualizing patches and seams on the area to focus on, rather than focusing on missing details.

This art of precious scars is a technique used as a means of analyzing the idea of ​​loss through synthesis and restoration of the destroyed and a metaphor for the possibility of rebirth.
Recovery from destructive events is possible through care and patching, not through hiding the damage, but by accepting a new state of the object or the whole life.
The world is a vase that is endlessly disassembled and sewn together again, continuing to bear traces of each event.

Non-human entities helped us put these vases together. In the beginning, there were vague forms, these were the shards themselves, created in collaboration with Latent Diffusion. Over time, they have grown in detail, drawing their stories more clearly, thanks to Jax Diffusion.

The code that puts everything together was written by Yulikolay, for which he is greatly appreciated.

metadata.name: A Bugged Forest #11
metadata.description:
A forest has stories to tell.
About times that were, about times that will be.
-
This project was minted in much unusual conditions. 
We gathered here, by 38 degrees heat. We belong to a crowd who loves stories, of civilisations at stake and deities, of afterlife and worship. We drank and hugged and chanted pagan hymns. We minted the Bugged Forest from our place on earth that we call Hell just for the fun of it. We are passionate, and loving, and angry and desperate. We, people of the soil, under a bugged sun.
-
This project is the long-form version of an algorithm that contains a bug. “The Bugged Tree”’s code was salvaged and stored and served as the core motivation and engine for an entire forest. Its concept is about releasing the control. I am a  byproduct of evolution, an iteration of that specie who wanted utter control, and which at some point, lost control over its own creation. As a generative artist, I chose to welcome the event of chance into my creative process. The symbolism in chance made me feel humble and free. Unwilling to make any change to a story that the Tree needed to tell me, as a listener, rather than a writer of my own idealised fantasies.
-
The iterations aren’t under control. They may be odd and off. We have to accept it. They are also plottable, press [s] in live mode to get a SVG. Attempt the plot at your own risk, as there’s a possibility for it to come near to impossibilities or cause paper or motor damage, and most certainly, a bugged drawing.
-
From Earth or from Hell, with love, yours truthfully, NFTBiker and zancan

metadata.name: Nounfall #70
metadata.description:
Nounfall is drawn exclusively from the 234 heads and 21 glasses that are used to build the current Nouns collection. The background colors are all pulled from the blessed Noun palette.

This is ok because Nouns are CC0, which basically means public domain. Check out nouns.wtf for more info.

They make for fun social media banners when cropped, if you wanna show off you fandom of Nouns.

C : Clear screen and start animation over
S : Save current image
1 -> 6 : Set pixel density to the respective number

So, if you want a high resolution file, tap `6` for it to redraw, and then `S` to save. You can also save while it's animating if you like, which is fun too.
